1. Working with Raster Data in terra (20 pts)

In this exercise, you will work with the same precipitation data as in class, but this time focus in on the Himalayan region of Asia.

  1. Load in the terra package. What version does it say you are using?

    library(tidyverse)
library("terra")
# using version 1.8-42

  2. Load in the precipitation data (global_precipitation.tif). What is the EPSG used in these data?

    glob_precip <- rast("global-precipitation.tif")
# the EPSG is 4326
plot(glob_precip)

    himalayan_ext <- ext(c(69.33, 97.15, 26.93, 40.37))

  3. Define a geographic extent object for the Himalayan region.

    The latitude and longitude of the Himalayas are, roughly:

    • Top left: (40.37, 69.33)

    • Bottom right: (26.93, 97.15)

  4. Crop the precipitation data to the Himalayan extent; what are resulting dimensions?

    Himalayan_precip <- crop(glob_precip, himalayan_ext)

  1. Plot the precipitation data for the Himalayan region.

  2. Add a descriptive title to the plot.

  3. Change the palette to that of topo.colors (use ?topo.colors for details) and print the resultant plot.

  4. Change the palette to one from ColorBrewer for sequential (continuous) data.

    #a
plot(Himalayan_precip)

    #b
plot(Himalayan_precip, main = "Himalayan Precipitation")

    #c
plot(Himalayan_precip, col = rainbow(n = 50))

    #d
Him_prec <- rev(hcl.colors(n = 20, palette = "PuBu"))

3. Working with Vector Data in terra (20 points)

Create a data frame of three peaks in the Himalayan region: (lat, lon)

  • K2: (35.93, 76.50)

  • Annapurna: (28.53, 83.81)

  • Mount Everest: (28.05, 86.91)

    Peaks <- data.frame(city = c("K2", "Annapurna", "Mount Everest"),
lat = c(35.93, 28.53, 28.05),
lon = c(76.50, 83.81, 86.91))
Peaks
    ##            city   lat   lon
## 1            K2 35.93 76.50
## 2     Annapurna 28.53 83.81
## 3 Mount Everest 28.05 86.91
  1. Create a SpatVector object from the data frame with peak data.

A quick note about plotting with terra:

When you run multiple plot functions (or a similar function adding something onto the plot, such as lines() or text()), you need to run all of the functions together at the same time. Running the lines one by one will give you an error like Error in graphicsplot.new has not been called yet.

You can either highlight all likes of code creating the plot and run them together or use the green arrow at the top of the code chunkeither option should work.

Him_vect <- vect(Peaks, crs = crs(Himalayan_precip))
Him_vect
##  class       : SpatVector 
##  geometry    : points 
##  dimensions  : 3, 1  (geometries, attributes)
##  extent      : 76.5, 86.91, 28.05, 35.93  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
##  coord. ref. : lon/lat WGS 84 (EPSG:4326) 
##  names       :          city
##  type        :         <chr>
##  values      :            K2
##                    Annapurna
##                Mount Everest

  1. Plot the precipitation data, and add the points of the peaks onto the plot.

    plot(Himalayan_precip, col = Him_prec)
plot(Him_vect, add = TRUE)

  2. Add labels to the points representing the peaks to the plot.

    plot(Himalayan_precip, col = Him_prec)
plot(Him_vect, add = TRUE)
text(Him_vect, labels = "city", pos = 4)

    #a
glob_elevation <- rast("global_elevation.tif")

    ## |---------|---------|---------|---------|=========================================

5. Converting Raster Objects to Spatial Vector Objects (20 points)

Create a plot that shows precipitation for the Himalayan region above 13,000 feet elevation.

Use a color palette from ColorBrewer and add a layer that is partially (50%) transparent to shade out regions below 13,000 feet. Take a look at the arguments for the polys function for how to set the color and transparency.

Himal_elev_min <- 13000

prec_himalayans <- himal_elev > Himal_elev_min
prec_himalayans[!prec_himalayans] <- NA

dry_poly <- as.polygons(!prec_himalayans, na.rm = F)

prec_hima_col <- hcl.colors(n = 50, palette = "GnBu")
prec_dry_col <- hcl.colors(n = 50, palette = "Grays")
plot(prec_himalayans, col = prec_hima_col) 
     polys(x = dry_poly, col = prec_dry_col, alpha = 0.5)
